Implement;
Day-to-day review Re-evaluate everyday;

What is the Risk Appetite? What is the Risk Capacity?
Risk appetite describes the amount and the type of risks which the firm is willing to take;
Risk capacity describes the maximum amount of risk which a firm can absorb;
FRB(Federal Reserve Board) conduct 2 stress testing exercises:

Dot-Frank Act Stress Test for asset size larger than USD 10 billion;
Comprehensive Capital Analysis and Review for asset size larger than USD 50 billion;

Most institutions set two types of limits:

Tier 1, risk that is specified, an overall limit by asset class;
Tier 2, more generalized risk related areas of business activities;

Moderan portfolio theory
Efficient frontier of Markowitz
Assumptions:

Investors are all rational(risk averse and want to maximize the utility);
Market is perfectly effcient(no extra trading cost and all infos are transaparent to all investors);
Returns are normally distributed;

The Markowitz efficient frontier demonstrates the portfolios in the capital market which is possible have the minimum variance with the same return; 

Capital Asset Pricing Model
The assumptions of CAPM are inherited from markowitz's efficient frontier:

Freely Access to the info by all investors;
No trading costs;
Allocation can be made in investment in any partial amount(perfect diversibility);
All investors can borrow or lend in Risk free rate;
Any individual investor can not affect the market prices;

In CAPM, all portfolios are combined by risk free investment and the portfolios on the effecint frontier, which is completely divisified.
